nds are in different countries, and the games are not Mah-jongg or Hearts.<br><br>Instead, Goldstein, 40, logs onto the Internet to roam through dangerous dungeons to slay dragons — along with tens of thousands of other players at the same time somewhere else in the world — in a role-playing game, EverQuest. She plays about 10 hours a week.<br><br>&quot;It's fun. It's social, and it's like stepping into a well-written adventure novel,&quot; said Goldstein, whose game name is &quot;Nin.&quot;<br><br>Concerns raised<br><br>More than 430,000 gamers pay $12.95 a month to play EverQuest. &quot; They roam electronic landscapes, chat with other players and solve quests, whether it be to slay an army of enemy creatures, escort a member of royalty to safety or recover a stolen artifact.<br><br>No matter how much one plays per month, the price is fixed. This &quot;persistent&quot; online game — meaning all events continue even after individual players log off — has proved addictive for many, earning its nickname: &quot;EverCrack.&quot; In fact, EverQuest addiction has raised renewed concerns in the media. Shawn Woolley, 21 recently shot himself in an apparent suicide after reportedly playing the game for up to 12 hours a day. His mother blames his &quot;obsession&quot; solely on game makers, although she admits her son had psychological problems before.<br><br>But — in moderation — online games have their good side, too. Goldstein still plays after 2 1/2 years because of the friendships she has formed. &quot;I have met almost all of them in real life, and we just have such a blast when we play,&quot; Goldstein said.<br><br>EverQuest is by far the most popular game of its kind in North America. There are other &quot;massively multiplayer&quot; role-playing games capable of supporting thousands of simultaneous players, such as Electronic Arts' Ultima Online, Microsoft's Asheron's Call and NCsoft's Lineage: The Blood Pledge. Others were previewed during the recent Electronic Entertainment Expo, including EA's The Sims Online and LucasArts' Star Wars Galaxies: An Empire Divided. Today, online gaming is a $200 million industry. Michael Garternberg, analyst at Jupiter Media Metrix, estimates it will climb to $2.5 billion in the next five years.<br><br>Casual OK, too<br><br>But time-consuming games like EverQuest aren't for everyone. A mission can take a few hours or a few days. Nor do all online players enjoy the more violent online &quot;3-D shooters,&quot; such as Counter-Strike or Unreal Tournament. <br><br>But millions of casual PC gamers have ditched the old standbys of Windows Solitaire and Minesweeper for online puzzle or card game diversions. These often use Flash, Shockwave or Java technology and do not require any files to be downloaded to the user's hard drive.<br><br>Another popular destination for solo and multiplayer games is RealArcade. Once the free RealArcade software is downloaded, players can log online to play one of 140 Web games or download titles to play from a hard drive. The games are free to download but will be limited in some way (only 10 free plays) until a credit card is used to unlock the full version. Depending on the game's depth, they cost $9.99, $14.99 or $19.99 each.<br><br>&quot;Our software will first detect if the player's PC can run the program, and then the game is automatically installed. It does everything for you&quot; said Molly McCarthy of RealNetworks.<br> <br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/upyrosissilvercaster.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pyrosis Silvercaster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/17/02 12:58:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm70.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=265.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left 